I take 2 x papers per semester as thats all I can manage given that I work 45 hours a week and have two kids and still need to maintain a good GPA for post grad.  I finely balance everything to get it done, but if the kids get sick, or if they have extra things on at the weekend or after school, then this can throw my study plans out the window. I find it quite hard to catch up the following week, so this stresses me out a bit.  I'll sometimes take a day off work (as annual leave) to catch up.  I find that every hour of my life is accounted for, whether it's study / work / the kids / exercise / life admin like the supermarket and if these get out of balance, I long for uni holidays or the mid semester break.  I know it's a challenging period of my life, but I do believe that it's only for a short time and it will pay off in the end.  I want my kids to know that you have to work at things to make life work, so I want them to see that sometimes it's a juggling act, but that you can do it.

One of the biggest challenges has been balancing the expectations of my lecturers with part-time paid work and social obligations/expectations. For example, it is difficult to thrive as a student without taking part-time work, particularly if you do not have any family support (financial or material) and are living away from home. Part-time work also offers a good way to build skills, including social and professional skills, learn to get on with others in a workplace environment, and builds confidence. For example, since I have already successfully applied for and been chosen for employment, I am not as anxious about my ability to present myself as a good candidate in interviews, write a CV and cover letter, etc. I have some idea of my worth as an employee and how to demonstrate that. Whereas, had I not had part-time employment, I think I would be very worried at the end of my degree about getting a job - more worried than I am now. However, lecturers usually expect you (or seem to expect you) to be always prioritising your studies, and that just isn't always feasible, particularly when there are times when there are 6 assignments due at once, and other times when there is nothing due, but your work hours stay the same the whole time. In addition, it is important to spend time with family, networking, and building relationships, and sometimes it is easy to feel that if you have spent any time out with friends or family, and then don't get the best mark on an assignment, that you could have done better by spending more time on it.

When I arrived at Massey University, I was very excited. However, when I joined my research group I was given the challenge of developing my PhD research proposal which involved techniques from food engineering. I was honest enough to tell my supervisor that mathematics was my weakest point and I had never done engineering or physics. As I tried my best to understand and develop these skills, the students in my group, as well as my supervisor would laugh at my mistakes. I felt that I was harshly judged, ridiculed. It hindered my progress for a while.

There was also a person who was very rude to me and would often speak to me in a harsh manner. I felt that I was being humiliated by this person in front of everyone. I felt that I was made to feel uncomfortable and unwelcome in this research group.  It was very hard to make friends with anyone. Another challenge I faced was having access to equipment for my experiment. This was crucial for my confirmation.

Despite the challenges I faced, I found people who helped me with my calculations and with my experiments. I was determined to learn a new skill and to use this new knowledge and new skill to make a difference in my country. I have come a long way since when I arrived in 2017. I am proud of the graceful manner in which I handled the hostility towards me. At the end of the day people who were challenging showed me what I never want to become towards other people.

It was an unexpected and an unpleasant experience at first but it taught me how to work among challenging people and I was able to learn about emotional intelligence and soft skills needed to work with people apart from scientific knowledge and skills. This experience also taught me resilience and showed me how resilient I truly am. However, I have never and would never treat anyone in the manner in which some of these people treated me.

My main issues are health-related. I have 4 auto-immune disorders which have for the past 9 years prevented me from being in employment. I started to study, as a way to still use my brain and do something (as I cannot sit around doing nothing), but in the last couple of years I have figured out what I want to do next career-wise and am focusing my future study plans on these areas. That being said, it all depends on whether my health will improve enough to be able to do full-time study (I just tried this semester and had to drop a paper as I couldn't cope). Sometimes this makes me feel frustrated, and left behind. I haven't achieved some of the expected life goals like having a partner and children, as I am mostly confined to my four walls. This causes me some anxiety as my biological clock is fast running out, however I put my trust in God that there is a plan for my life and it will all work out. I have found purpose through studying, through going through grief counselling, and self-help courses to re-evaluate my life and see that the illnesses happened for a reason. I used to be deeply clinically depressed, but the illness afforded me the time to stop, rest, and begin the healing journey, and I have worked really hard to break through limiting beliefs that left me hopeless, vulnerable, and suicidal. I am proud to say that I am no longer depressed, and I have hope, purpose, and meaning in my life, despite not having achieved all that I want to ... yet.
I also help my aging parents with their errands, and cooking meals etc which cuts into the time and energy I have to study and achieve my goals. Sometimes I feel a little trapped, as my siblings with their families, are overseas so the onus is on me to care for our parents. Yet, I too have goals beyond this limited existence. But I am also grateful that I get quality time with my parents, and that I can help them.

The biggest challenge has been trying to get others to realise that when I am at home studying I'm not simply doing nothing. 

Another challenge is not having the classroom environment as I am doing distance. I am just very lucky that I have incredible lecturers who encourage participation through forums.

One of the biggest challenges is dealing with the workload and not being supported by supervisors. 
Some supervisors are just not available and do not make time for you, so you feel undervalued and that you are not worth their time. It is hard when they are meant to support and guide you as the experts, and you end up feeling inadequate and lost. If they just managed their time better and made themselves available then it would not give rise to such feelings of not being worth their effort and/or time. 
I have worked in many professional environments and have never had such difficulties with trying to communicate with “senior” staff. They need to function as supervisors and actually guide the students, it is a time inefficient process for the student to not have clear direction, all it takes is regular discussions (at their time) to achieve this. This seriously affects my (and I know others) satisfaction with my time as a doctoral student, and it reflects directly back on Massey when I discuss this with friends, family and colleagues. I know I am not alone.

The biggest challenge for me has actually been the beginning of each semester. I have completed my degree 100% via distance, and the beginning of the semester is always the challenging time. Getting resources (readings) sent to Australia within a decent time frame is a challenge (they often don't arrive until Week four or five - way too late), and then the next one is always working out exactly what each lecturer wants on stream. Each tutor loads stream differently, with different requirements, different expectations and different formats of stream. So often I am 'behind' for the first month of semester - then I slot into a routine and all is good.
The other challenge has been my age - I am 47 and sometimes there is a small wave of panic that floats over me as I meet other women my age who already have established careers and incomes...and I am still at Uni. I do get a sense from society that as I am not in a specific career-path, ie, nursing, teaching, etc, that I am just 'mucking around' at Uni. Actually, it is the complete opposite and I would love to be in paid employment of course, and that is what I am working towards.

I am afriad of failure, but also I am trying hard to work within a self-managed envelope of reasoned self-fairness, trying to balance focus and productivity with reduced stress and anxiety. Practically, anxiety manifests as sleep problems or exhaustion. Persistent self evaluation of my mental state and self acknowledgement of personal limits helps, but lately I have felt I am crossing in to crisis too regularly, often where I am pushing myself too hard. The problem becomes difficult to manage when identification of self care may be interpreted for inertia or lack of motivation, leading self doubt and triggering fear of failure. In other words, learning to trust oneself that balancing rest and restoration is important, even when deadlines are bearing down upon oneself.
